post_text: FINAL OPPORTUNITY- The RV Chapter 1766 of the Science National Honor Society is accepting its first-year applications for membership. The National Board requires that prospective members be full-time 11th or 12th grade RV students during the current school year. You must have and maintain a 3.0 GPA across all courses and a 3.5 GPA across all science courses in addition to meeting other criteria including being a Student in Good Standing according to the RVRHS Student Handbook. Online applications are being accepted until 3pm TODAY. Click the link on the website news item to access the form.

Expect a communication from Principal Martin’s Office early next week outlining specific details about the plan for this week.

Attention Parents/Guardians: We are correcting a technology issue we experienced from our end on our GENESIS platform. If you have not logged into GENESIS within the last 24 hours, please log into your Parent Portal account and resubmit the 3 required forms. Please note that the forms are pre-populated with the information that you have already completed (as the parent/guardian). This will require minimal time to resubmit. The forms that must be resubmitted include: 1:WORLD Initiative & Technology Forms 2020-21; RVRHS Opening Day Required Form 2020-21; and Student Medical Information Form 2020-21.

Submission of the 1:WORLD form is a mandatory requirement prior to your child receiving their school issued electronic device (MacBook). We are excited to begin device deployment starting August 24th! If your child has any school materials (textbooks, calculators, etc.) from the spring semester please make sure to bring them with you when you pick up your device.

post_text: Congratulations to 2015 RV alum, Jade Overton who took the Physician’s Pledge on August 7th, 2020 and was granted her “White Coat“ as she entered Drexel University's College of Medicine. After completing her undergraduate degree from Rowan University in Biology, Jade entered the Drexel DPMS program in July of 2019, where she earned a Master’s Degree in Biomedical Sciences. Her primary interests include women’s health, and advancing healthcare access for underserved populations. She strives to give back to her community through mentoring current pre-med students, tutoring, and advocating for those that are underrepresented in medicine.

post_text:
As part of our Vision 2020 Strategic Plan, RV embarked on a One to World initiative, aligned with our mission, core values, and student-centered goals. By leveraging technologies that promote project-based, authentic, and personalized learning, RV will be ensuring that tomorrow’s RV students will be academically, socially, and emotionally engaged learners and citizens. In order for students to begin the school year ready and equipped with his/her device, parents are asked to begin planning now for when you and your child will come to RV to acquire the MacBook Air.

Our pick-up center, located in the Performing Arts Center (PAC) will be open on:
● Monday, August 24 through Friday, August 28, from 8 am to 7 pm
● Saturday, August 29, from 9 am to 2 pm and
● Monday, August 31, from 8 am to 7 pm

Students, accompanied by a parent/guardian, can choose the time and date that works for them to pick-up the device. Please check the RV website 1:World page (https://www.rvrhs.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=371455&type=d) for further information on the deployment process.

post_text: In light of the recent demonstrations against racism in our country, the RV Civic Engagement Club mobilized to provide a forum for RV community members to express their support for this important movement. We all have a responsibility because we all must play a role in being part of meaningful change -- and do it peacefully and productively - to address racism in America. We may not be together in person, but we can stand up together against racism.

post_text: Congratulations to the cast and crew of the Red Devil Dramatics production of “The Outsiders” which has been awarded a Foxy by Montclair State University for Outstanding Achievement in Choreography or Movement. The goal of Montclair State University is to promote and advance the commitment to high-quality straight play production in New Jersey’s secondary schools. The awards honor the accomplishments of individual achievement of both students and educators in the areas of performance, direction, design and technical theatre, as well as outstanding productions in drama, comedy, classical and new work.

The awards honor the accomplishments of individual achievement of both students and educators in the areas of performance, direction, design and technical theatre, as well as outstanding productions in drama, comedy, classical and new work.

post_text: Congratulations to 2011 RV alum and NJROTC cadet, Lt. Sam Krakower, currently serving as the US Coast Guard representative liaison to the U.S. Congress on Capitol Hill, briefing officials on all fiscal & administrative matters concerning the USCG. Krakower attended the U.S. Coast Guard Academy in New London, CT, receiving his commission as an Ensign with a handshake from President Obama, in 2015. Sam has served aboard three different Coast Guard cutters with his last tour aboard the USCGC Polar Star as the Operations Officer, deployed to the Antarctic in support of Naval Support Forces and the National Science Foundation at McMurdo Station.

post_text: Congratulations to 2018 RV alum, Justin Foster, who is among RCBC’s first set of 3+1 Inclusive Education graduates. Justin plans to enter the K-6 school system after earning his bachelor’s degree. Justin is one of two students slated to earn RCBC’s President’s Award during this year's graduation ceremony. For Justin, community college has been about the relationships formed and the interactions with not only his peers but also his professors. Justin’s passion for inclusive education was ignited at 15 years old when working at a special needs camp in Missouri for the summer. Before the pandemic, he worked 30-40 hours per week at an area elementary school and swim school to ensure he could travel to various countries to experience different cultures.

post_text:
Congratulations to RV Business Administrator, Ms. Lisa Giovanelli who was chosen as a recipient of a Distinguished Service Award of the New Jersey Association of School Business Officials. The award is given to school business officials who have performed outstanding service in a specific area, above and beyond their typical responsibilities in the district, community or profession.

During her tenure at Rancocas Valley Regional High School, Lisa has overseen several major projects including the renovation of the main campus turf field athletic complex and the Annex building to house administrative offices as well as the RVPREP and FLIP programs. This past year, Lisa coordinated the construction of the main campus security vestibule and adjoining office space funded by a million grant from the Burlington County Freeholders. With the passage of the referendum in October, Lisa is currently overseeing safety, security, and health-related renovations to both the main campus and Annex.

RCBC Summer Registration is now open. This is a great opportunity for students a jump start on college course in our Summer I term beginning May 15 with classes at our current tuition rate. To help students begin the process of Fall Registration, RCBS is scheduling virtual appointments with the admissions team to speak with students via video or phone appointments.

In lieu of a placement test, RCBC will be using the following resources as a measure for placement in English or Math courses: standardized test scores (SAT, ACT, ASVAB, PARCC) and review of high school/college transcripts. Transcripts may be mailed to the Office of Outreach and Admissions at 900 College Circle, Mount Laurel, NJ 08054 or transmitted directly via Naviance by contacting the Guidance Department. Students with questions or concerns, can contact RCBC at admissions@rcbc.edu or (856) 222-9311, ext. 1199 (please leave a message for a callback within 24-48 business hours).

post_text: To keep students safe, and in alignment with public health guidance and school closures, the College Board will not administer the SAT or SAT Subject Tests on May 2nd and June 6th. If safe from a public health standpoint, the College Board will provide weekend SAT administrations every month through the end of the calendar year beginning in August. This includes a new administration in September and the previously scheduled tests on August 29, October 3, November 7, and December 5. Students can register for these administrations starting in May. Please check the RV website as further information becomes available.

post_text: The AP exams will only include topics and skills covered in class by early March. Most exams will have one or two free-response questions, and each question will be timed separately. Students will need to write and submit their responses within the allotted time for each question. Most exams will be 45 minutes long and include an additional 5 minutes for uploading. Students will need to access the online testing system 30 minutes early to get set up. Students will be able to take exams at home on any device they have access to—computer, tablet, or smartphone. They will be able to either type and upload their responses or write responses by hand and submit a photo via their cell phone. Students taking AP world language and culture exams will complete two spoken tasks consistent with free-response questions three and four on the current AP Exam as written responses will not be required.

post_text: The Philadelphia Eagles have selected Temple linebacker and 2015 RV alum Shaun Bradley in the NFL draft. Shaun played running back and defensive back for coach Dan Haussman earning first team all-county as an RV senior after rushing for 1,467 yards and 22 touchdowns on 188 carries. Shaun also lettered in basketball and track earning the RV Male Athlete of the Year Award in 2014-15. At 6-foot-1 and 235 pounds, Shaun has been key for the middle of the Temple Owls’ defense, leading the team with 87 tackles, eight for a loss, and broke up three passes as a senior in 2019.

post_text: The vernal equinox (first day of Spring) will occur on Thursday (March 19) at 11:49:28 p.m. EDT (0349 GMT on March 20). At that moment, the sun will appear directly overhead about 50 miles (80 kilometers) south of Gorontalo, a province of Indonesia on the island of Sulawesi, on the equator in the Gulf of Tomini. This will be the earliest that the vernal equinox will occur across the contiguous United States in 124 years due to the leap year and daylight saving time.

As the country deals with the effects of the Coronavirus (COVID-19), Comcast is taking immediate steps to help connect more low-income families to the Internet at home. Effective Monday, March 16, 2020, anyone who signs up for Internet Essentials will receive two free months of Internet service. We are also increasing the speed of the program to 25 Mbps downloads, and 3 Mbps uploads for all new and existing customers.

After your first two free months expire, you can either cancel the service (which you can do at any time) or keep it as a regular paying Internet Essentials customer. You will receive an easy to use self-install-kit that includes a cable modem (to receive service at your home) with a WiFi router (to connect your devices without wires). There is no term contract or credit check and no shipping fee for equipment.

You can apply using this link https://www.internetessentials.com/Apply or please call 1-855-8-INTERNET (1-855-846-8376).

post_text: The RVRHS Student Wellness Fair will be held on March 12th during all student preps in the Small Gym. This event brings together students, staff and community health and wellness services to promote mental, emotional and physical health and student well-being. The RVRHS Student Wellness Fair looks to provide awareness of what is available in our community to support students and their families. By creating awareness of these wellness resources, we hope to reduce barriers that often interfere with students seeking and receiving the support they need and deserve. This event will provide students with the knowledge and means to start communication with these beneficial resources.

post_text: Inklings is excited to announce the winners of its First Annual Poetry Drop Box contest! For two months, Inklings Literary Magazine received over 30 submissions from across the student body. A panel of student judges read and evaluated the pieces and selected the following winners: 1st Place (Trish Miller), 2nd Place (Cyanee Isom), and 3rd Place (Skylar Cowperthwait). The selected poets received a gift card from Barnes & Noble and will be published in the Spring issue of Inklings.

post_text: On Saturday, February 29 at the Liberty Bell Classic held at Dan Campos Fitness in Philadelphia, Josh Green and Elijah Ghaly were the first RV students to participate in a Powerlifting Competition. They have been training fiercely the past 3 months for this competition. Under the coaching of Donna Aromando, School Counselor and USAP & USAPL Certified Coach and Competitor, Josh earned a Gold medal in his age/weight group, as well as personal records in Squat and Deadlift. Elijah took a Silver in his age/weight class and a persona record in Squat. Congratulations to Josh and Elijah!

post_text: Rancocas Valley Regional High School will host the 9th annual Devil Dash on Friday, May 29th starting at 3pm on the turf field to benefit the Pat Tillman Foundation, awards for RV seniors entering the armed services and funding for veteran causes. We have donated a PTSD dog "Echo" for a marine veteran. This event also raises awareness to healthy life choices, and living an emotionally, socially and physically healthy and satisfying life. Over 800 racers and 150+ volunteers participated last year raising over $27,000 in donations. Form a team of 2 or 4, male, female or co-ed. Receive a free t-shirt and swag bag! Odd numbered teams are welcomed, but not timed. The community donation is $20 per racer. To register for the event please visit www.rvrhs.com and click on the Student Activities Tab, then RV Devil Dash, and select forms to register with the waiver. Please email daromando@rvrhs.com or call 609-267-0830, ext. 3253 with any questions.

post_text: Congratulations to the Boys Indoor Track and Field team for winning the program's first indoor track Sectional Championship in school history. The team was led by individual sectional champions: Miekel House (55m dash) and Jordon Floyd (High Jump). The team also received key points from the following athletes who also qualified for the state championship meet: Tahmir Clark (High Jump), Daniel Dayrell (55m hurdles), Rahmier Patterson (400m and 4x400 relay), Jonah Wood (Shot Put), Gabriel Wilson (4x4 relay), Gavin Farrell (4x4 relay), and Ryan Maggs (4x4 relay).

post_text: RV FLIP students enjoyed a luncheon with their main campus pals at the Annex complex on Wednesday, February 12th as part of the Best Buddies Club. The students text and phone each other during the school year as well as participating in various outings and events. According to the club moderator and Social Studies teacher, Ms. Karen Carlson, more than 100 students are involved in the program. Special education teacher, Ms. Natasha Serafini explained that the program ensures that students of all abilities have the same opportunities for social interactions and experiences.

post_text: RVRHS is pleased to announce the hiring of Mr. Bill Fields as our Safety and Security Coordinator. Fields, as an officer with the Mount Holly Township Police Department, served as our student resource officer from 1999-2001 and managed the SRO program from 2013-2018. The RV administration created the new position as part of the school’s Vision 2020 strategic plan to enhance security in the school building and on campus. The coordinator will oversee all aspects of our security system, including 200 surveillance cameras and various safety procedures, including visitor registrations, lockdown drills and emergency plans. Fields, who retired from the force with the rank of lieutenant in 2019, is familiar with all these duties as well as the school community. Fields has a master’s degree in criminal justice and public policy from Liberty University.

post_text: Congratulations to sophomore's Sarah Venverloh and Shianne Figueroa whose film won first place for best movie trailer in the Artist Alike Film Festival. A number of schools from across New Jersey submit films and only the top six in each category are chosen to be screened at the Artist Alike Film Festival and the winning films will be screened at the Garden State Film Festival in March. Sarah and Shianne worked on their film as part of a class project in Mr. Marmarou's Audio Video Technology class. This is the third year in a row that RV students have placed first in the Artist Alike Film Festival.

post_text: The RVRHS Board of Education, administrators, and staff cordially invite parents/guardians to attend the Spring Semester Back-to-School Night on Thursday, February 20th from 7pm-9pm. The staff will be present and the emphasis of the evening will be on offering descriptions of our curriculum, programs, and classroom policies for the second semester. Counselors and administrative staff will also be available throughout the evening in their respective offices. Refreshments will be served in the cafeteria beginning at the end of Block 2. RV’s school store, The Devil’s Den, will be open for business in the cafeteria (cash or check only). Following the end of Block 5, you may return to a class for individual questions about your student’s performance.

post_text: On Tuesday February 4, RV students Charles Rumberger, Jacen Januseski, Devin Fox, Shane Langefeld, and Ta'Kai Knox. traveled to Westampton with Mr. Eleuteri to compete in the 2020 New Jersey Consumer Bowl. This is a yearly competition sponsored by the NJ Consumer Affairs Division of the Office of the Attorney General where students answer various questions related to consumer law and consumer awareness. The RV Team placed second to Moorestown Friends in a close and spirited competition after advancing past the first round by defeating three other Burlington County schools. Each member received a T shirt and a participation certificate.

post_text: Congratulations to the RV FIRST Robotics team who were approved at the Lockheed-Martin Critical Design Review (CDR) on January 31st to proceed in the fabrication of their robot to participate in this year's competition.In INFINITE RECHARGESM, two alliances work to protect FIRST City from approaching asteroids caused by a distant space skirmish. Each Alliance, along with their trusty droids, race to collect and score Power Cells in order to energize their Shield Generator for maximum protection. To activate stages of the Shield Generator, droids manipulate their Control Panels after scoring a specific number of Power Cells. Near the end of the match, droids race to their Rendezvous Point to get their Shield Generator operational in order to protect the city!

post_text: The RVRHS Playschool is accepting applications for the spring 2020 semester. This 8 week program is free and available to children between the ages of 3 to 5 years old. Children must be completely toilet trained and from one of the RV sending districts. Our program meets on Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday from 9:45am to 11:45am. We focus on social skills and offer the children, arts and crafts, activities, language arts, story time, science experiments, dramatic play, block building, songs, music, and a healthy snack. The program will begin on Wednesday March 18th. For more information and an application please contact Diane Holzschuh at: dholzschuh@rvrhs.com

post_text: Congratulations to Ben Kirk who was awarded the $3000 Richard M. Smith scholarship for Music Education by the SJ Choral Directors Association at the 62nd Annual SJ High School Choral Festival. This award is given to a graduating senior member of the Senior HS Chorus planning to further their education in the field of Music Education. Applicants are all personally interviewed by a selection committee, which determines the recipient on the basis of talent and scholastic achievement. In addition, to singing a piece by Gabriel Faure, Ben wrote an essay about his past choral experience, growing up with a choir director parent, sister, and sister currently studying music education.

RVRHS Retirement & Recognition Committee Accepting Nominations for VIP & Community Member
The RVRHS Retirement & Recognition Committee is now accepting nominations for both VIP and Community Member awards for the 31st Annual Program. The VIP program honors RV alumnae who have distinguished themselves in their chosen fields and/or been recognized for their positive contributions locally, regionally, or nationally. Additionally, the program likes to show its appreciation to community members who have given freely of their time and efforts on behalf of the students at Rancocas Valley. Those selected will be honored at the annual awards banquet in June. If you wish to nominate someone for the VIP or Community Member Program, please click on the link following this announcement to access the form. Nominations must be received no later than Monday, February 24, 2020.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScPWV-Oda4CZd46JKvDrWASqZ77m9JwbPRtlJWQYZR5u3ZQXQ/viewform

The match is rescheduled to take place on Wednesday, January 22nd at 6:00PM in the RV Main Gym.

post_text:
Congratulations to Ms. Bouchra Heiba named as RV's choice for the Governor's Educator of the Year Award. Students described her as one of "the most dedicated and engaged teachers ... inspiring students of all backgrounds." Others noted Ms. Heiba is "selfless in the classroom, caring about and believing in each of her students without hesitation". Colleagues and alumni commented on her numerous contributions to the school and greater community including Red & White Night, Homecoming, the French Club, cultural trips abroad, the Vision 2020 Equity and Technology committees, and much more.

Congratulations to Mr. Raj Mackara selected as the RV Educational Services Professional of the Year. Most deserving of the honor, colleagues described Mackara as being "the most important entity in the school" and "a fixture here for 35 years" who "is everywhere in the building and always ready to listen to students and staff". Others noted his fairness and empathy adding that students "read through his tough love as they knew he truly cares about their well-being."
